hook.real_world_problem:
Your order-service needs to tell notification-service, analytics-service, and inventory-service that an order was placed. Without Kafka:

```java
// Synchronous calls — all must succeed for the order to complete:
paymentService.charge(order);
notificationService.sendSms(order);        // if down → order fails!
analyticsService.recordOrder(order);       // if slow → user waits
inventoryService.reserveStock(order);      // if down → order fails!
```

**With Kafka:**
```java
// One publish — everything else is decoupled:
paymentService.charge(order);              // synchronous (critical path)
kafkaTemplate.send("order-events", order);
// ↑ notification, analytics, inventory
//   all receive this event asynchronously
//   order returns to user immediately ✓
```

**Spring Kafka KafkaTemplate:**
```java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    private final KafkaTemplate<String, OrderEvent> kafkaTemplate;

    public Order placeOrder(OrderRequest req) {
        Order order = orderRepo.save(new Order(req));

        // Publish event — returns immediately:
        kafkaTemplate.send("order-events",
            order.getId(),              // key → same partition for same order
            new OrderEvent(order));     // value → the event

        return order;  // user gets response in < 50ms
    }
}
// notification-service, analytics-service consume 'order-events' independently
```

One line. Order response time drops from 500ms to 50ms. Services are decoupled. That's KafkaTemplate.

concept_explanation.kafka_template_basics:
**KafkaTemplate — the Spring Kafka producer:**

```java
import org.springframework.kafka.core.KafkaTemplate;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;
import java.util.concurrent.CompletableFuture;

@Service
public class OrderEventPublisher {
    private final KafkaTemplate<String, OrderEvent> kafkaTemplate;

    OrderEventPublisher(KafkaTemplate<String, OrderEvent> kafkaTemplate) {
        this.kafkaTemplate = kafkaTemplate;
    }

    // Simple send — fire and forget:
    public void publishOrderPlaced(Order order) {
        kafkaTemplate.send("order-events", new OrderEvent(order, "ORDER_PLACED"));
    }

    // Send with KEY — guarantees same-key messages go to same partition:
    public void publishWithKey(Order order) {
        kafkaTemplate.send(
            "order-events",         // topic
            order.getId(),           // key → determines partition
            new OrderEvent(order, "ORDER_PLACED")  // value
        );
    }

    // Async send with callback:
    public void publishWithCallback(Order order) {
        kafkaTemplate.send("order-events", order.getId(), new OrderEvent(order))
            .whenComplete((result, ex) -> {
                if (ex != null) {
                    System.err.println("Failed to send event: " + ex.getMessage());
                    // retry, log to dead-letter, alert oncall...
                } else {
                    System.out.printf("Sent to topic=%s partition=%d offset=%d%n",
                        result.getRecordMetadata().topic(),
                        result.getRecordMetadata().partition(),
                        result.getRecordMetadata().offset());
                }
            });
    }
}
```

**Spring Boot 3.x note**: `kafkaTemplate.send()` now returns `CompletableFuture<SendResult<K,V>>` (not `ListenableFuture`). Use `.whenComplete()` for callbacks.

concept_explanation.producer_configuration:
**Producer configuration via @Bean:**

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.ProducerConfig;
import org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer;
import org.springframework.kafka.core.*;
import org.springframework.kafka.support.serializer.JsonSerializer;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

@Configuration
public class KafkaProducerConfig {

    @Bean
    public ProducerFactory<String, OrderEvent> producerFactory() {
        Map<String, Object> config = new HashMap<>();
        config.put(ProducerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        config.put(ProducerConfig.KEY_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG,   StringSerializer.class);
        config.put(ProducerConfig.VALUE_SERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, JsonSerializer.class);
        config.put(ProducerConfig.ACKS_CONFIG, "all");       // durability
        config.put(ProducerConfig.RETRIES_CONFIG, 3);         // retry on failure
        config.put(ProducerConfig.ENABLE_IDEMPOTENCE_CONFIG, true); // exactly-once
        return new DefaultKafkaProducerFactory<>(config);
    }

    @Bean
    public KafkaTemplate<String, OrderEvent> kafkaTemplate(
            ProducerFactory<String, OrderEvent> pf) {
        return new KafkaTemplate<>(pf);
    }
}
```

**Key producer configs explained:**
- `acks=all`: all in-sync replicas must acknowledge → no data loss
- `retries=3`: retry on transient failures (network blip)
- `enable.idempotence=true`: exactly-once delivery (deduplicates retries)
- `batch-size=16384`: batch small messages for efficiency (16KB)
- `linger.ms=1`: wait 1ms to batch more messages before sending

concept_explanation.message_keys:
**Message keys — why they matter:**

```java
// With key: orders for same orderId always go to same partition
// → All events for order ORD-001 arrive in order to consumers

// For a Zerodha trade:
kafkaTemplate.send("trade-events",
    trade.getSymbol(),    // key='TCS' → all TCS trades in one partition
    new TradeEvent(trade));

// For order updates:
kafkaTemplate.send("order-events",
    order.getId(),        // key='ORD-001' → ORDER_PLACED, ORDER_CONFIRMED,
    event);               // ORDER_SHIPPED all in partition order

// WITHOUT key: random partition → events for same order out of order!
// ORD-001: ORDER_PLACED → partition 0
// ORD-001: ORDER_SHIPPED → partition 2  (consumer 2 gets this FIRST!)
// ORD-001: ORDER_CONFIRMED → partition 1
// → Consumer sees: SHIPPED before CONFIRMED → broken logic!
```

**Rule**: use the entity ID as the key when you need events for the same entity to arrive in order.

concept_explanation.testing:
**Testing producers with @EmbeddedKafka:**

```java
import org.springframework.kafka.test.context.EmbeddedKafka;
import org.springframework.kafka.test.utils.KafkaTestUtils;
import org.springframework.boot.test.context.SpringBootTest;
import org.apache.kafka.clients.consumer.ConsumerRecord;
import org.springframework.kafka.core.ConsumerFactory;

@SpringBootTest
@EmbeddedKafka(
    partitions = 1,
    brokerProperties = {"listeners=PLAINTEXT://localhost:9099",
                         "port=9099"}
)
class OrderEventPublisherTest {
    @Autowired OrderEventPublisher publisher;
    @Autowired ConsumerFactory<String, String> consumerFactory;

    @Test
    void publishOrderPlaced_messageAppearsOnTopic() throws Exception {
        // Arrange:
        Order order = new Order("ORD-001", "TCS", 10, 3890.0);

        // Act:
        publisher.publishOrderPlaced(order);

        // Assert — consume from embedded Kafka:
        Map<String, Object> configs = KafkaTestUtils.consumerProps(
            "test-group", "true", embeddedKafka);
        Consumer<String, String> consumer = consumerFactory.createConsumer("g", "c");
        consumer.subscribe(List.of("order-events"));
        ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofSeconds(5));

        assertFalse(records.isEmpty());
        ConsumerRecord<String, String> record = records.iterator().next();
        assertTrue(record.value().contains("ORD-001"));
        consumer.close();
    }
}
```

**Test application.properties:**
```properties
# Override Kafka URL for tests:
spring.kafka.bootstrap-servers=${spring.embedded.kafka.brokers}
```

